PART 1 — What #pragma pack Does
It changes struct member alignment rules and can reduce padding.
Normal alignment (common):
char   = 1short  = 2int    = 4double = 8pointer(64-bit) = 8

PART 2 — Basic #pragma pack(1)
Code
#include <stdio.h>#pragma pack(1)struct A {    char a;    int b;};int main() {    printf("%zu\n", sizeof(struct A));}
Output
5
Memory Diagram
Offset: 0 1 2 3 4        a b b b b
No padding.

PART 3 — Normal Version (No pack)
Code
struct A {    char a;    int b;};
Output
8
Layout
0 a1-3 pad4-7 b

PART 4 — #pragma pack()
Restore default alignment.
Code
#pragma pack(1)struct A {    char a;    int b;};#pragma pack()struct B {    char a;    int b;};
Output
sizeof(A)=5sizeof(B)=8

PART 5 — #pragma pack(push,1) and pop
Best practice.
Code
#include <stdio.h>struct Normal1 {    char a;    int b;};#pragma pack(push,1)struct Packed {    char a;    int b;};#pragma pack(pop)struct Normal2 {    char a;    int b;};int main() {    printf("%zu\n", sizeof(struct Normal1));    printf("%zu\n", sizeof(struct Packed));    printf("%zu\n", sizeof(struct Normal2));}
Output
858

Meaning
push = save current packing state1    = set pack(1)pop  = restore previous state

PART 6 — Dangerous Global pack
Code
#pragma pack(1)struct Packet {    char a;    int b;};struct Unexpected {    char x;    int y;};
Output
sizeof(Packet)=5sizeof(Unexpected)=5
Problem: second struct also packed unintentionally.

